  <!-- FAQ Schema -->
  <script type="application/ld+json" is:inline>
    {
      "@context": "https://schema.org",
      "@type": "FAQPage",
      "mainEntity": [
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "how much capital gains tax calculator",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "<p>A capital gains tax calculator helps you estimate your tax liability by entering your purchase price, sale price, annual ordinary income, and holding period. The calculator automatically handles the math, applying U.S. federal and state rates or international tax rules to show how much you owe.</p>"
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "what is capital gains tax",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "<p>Capital gains tax is a tax levied on the profit made from selling an asset, such as stocks, bonds, cryptocurrency, or real estate, for more than its purchase price (cost basis). It is only triggered when you sell or dispose of the asset, not while you hold it.</p>"
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "how much is capital gains tax",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "<p>The amount of capital gains tax you pay depends on how long you held the asset (short-term vs. long-term) and your total taxable income. Short-term gains are taxed at ordinary income rates (up to 37% in the U.S.), while long-term gains enjoy preferential rates of 0%, 15%, or 20% federally.</p>"
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "how to avoid capital gains tax",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "<p>You can minimize or avoid capital gains tax by holding assets for more than a year to qualify for long-term rates, utilizing tax-advantaged accounts (like IRAs or 401ks), offseting gains with capital losses (tax-loss harvesting), donating appreciated assets to charity, or using primary residence exclusions on property sales.</p>"
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "how does capital gains tax work",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "<p>Capital gains tax works by calculating the difference between your asset's sale price and its original purchase price (including transaction fees). If you have a positive net gain, that profit is subject to tax. The rate applied is determined by whether the asset was held for a short-term (one year or less) or long-term (more than one year) period.</p>"
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "what is the capital gains tax rate",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "<p>For long-term assets held over a year, federal capital gains tax rates in the U.S. are 0%, 15%, or 20% depending on your income. For short-term assets held a year or less, the rate is the same as your standard progressive ordinary income tax bracket, ranging from 10% to 37%.</p>"
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "what is long term capital gains tax",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "<p>Long-term capital gains tax is a tax on profits from selling capital assets that you have owned for more than one year. These gains receive preferential tax treatment compared to ordinary income to encourage long-term investing.</p>"
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "what is the long term capital gains tax rate",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "<p>The U.S. long-term capital gains tax rates are 0%, 15%, or 20% depending on your filing status and annual taxable income. Additionally, high earners may be subject to a 3.8% Net Investment Income Tax (NIIT) and state income taxes.</p>"
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "when do you pay capital gains tax on real estate",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "<p>You pay capital gains tax on real estate in the tax year you sell the property. However, if the property was your primary residence for at least two out of the five years prior to the sale, you may exclude up to $250,000 of gain (single) or $500,000 (married filing jointly) from your taxable income.</p>"
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "how to avoid capital gains tax on real estate",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "<p>To avoid capital gains tax on real estate, you can live in the home as your primary residence for at least 2 of the 5 years before selling to claim the section 121 exclusion. For investment properties, you can defer taxes by reinvesting the proceeds into another investment property using a Section 1031 exchange.</p>"
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "what is short term capital gains tax",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "<p>Short-term capital gains tax applies to profits from selling capital assets held for one year or less. These gains do not receive preferential tax treatment and are taxed as ordinary income.</p>"
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "how much is short term capital gains tax",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "<p>Short-term capital gains are taxed at your marginal ordinary income tax rate. In the U.S., these rates range from 10% to 37% depending on your income bracket and filing status, plus any applicable state taxes.</p>"
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "how to avoid paying capital gains tax on inherited property",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "<p>When you inherit property, the cost basis is typically 'stepped up' to the fair market value of the property on the date of the donor's death. This means if you sell the inherited property immediately, your taxable capital gains will be minimal or zero since your basis matches the sale price.</p>"
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "where can i find a capital gains tax estimator?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "<p>You can find a capital gains tax estimator right here at the top of this page. This free online calculator estimates U.S. federal and state taxes, as well as localized rules for Canada, the UK, Australia, Europe, and India, all client-side for complete privacy.</p>"
          }
        }
      ]
    }
  </script>

