      <div class="text-xs text-slate leading-relaxed flex flex-col gap-3">
        <p>
          Capital Gains Tax (CGT) is levied on the profits earned from selling
          capital assets like stocks, bonds, cryptocurrency, or real estate. The
          taxable gain is generally calculated as the sale price minus the
          purchase price and eligible costs (such as transaction fees or
          improvements).
        </p>

        <h4 class="font-semibold text-primary">
          1. Short-Term vs. Long-Term Gains
        </h4>
        <div>
          Holding periods determine whether gains are taxed at ordinary income
          rates or concessionary rates:
          <ul class="list-disc pl-4 flex flex-col gap-1 mt-1">
            <li>
              <strong>United States</strong>: Assets held &gt; 1 year are taxed
              at preferential long-term rates (0%, 15%, 20%). Short-term gains
              are taxed at ordinary income slabs.
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Australia</strong>: Assets held &gt; 1 year receive a 50%
              discount on the taxable gain.
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Canada</strong>: No distinction in holding period, but
              capital gains have a 50% inclusion rate (increasing to 66.67% on
              annual gains over $250k).
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>India</strong>: Varies by asset. Listed stocks require 12
              months for long-term status, while real estate requires 24 months.
            </li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <h4 class="font-semibold text-primary">2. Sub-National Taxes</h4>
        <p>
          State or provincial capital gains taxes apply in the US and Canada. In
          the US, state tax applies to your total gain. In Canada, provincial
          tax applies to the included portion of the gain.
        </p>

        <h4 class="font-semibold text-primary">
          3. Net Investment Income Tax (NIIT)
        </h4>
        <p>
          In the US, an additional 3.8% NIIT applies to investment income if
          your total MAGI exceeds threshold limits ($200,000 for single,
          $250,000 for joint filers).
        </p>
      </div>
